            "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 5",
            "content": "## Analyze Questions\r\n\r\n**25. In the chapter's coffee shop example, which of the following is the root reason the owner cannot determine which supplier problems affect daily sales?**\r\n\r\nA. The owner does not know SQL\r\n\r\nB. The data is stored across disconnected spreadsheets with inconsistent identifiers, so the records cannot be linked\r\n\r\nC. The shop does not use Power BI\r\n\r\nD. The owner has not enrolled in BITM330\r\n\r\n**26. Chapter 1 says decisions depend on whether data is captured, structured, retrieved, and interpreted responsibly. If a hospital captures patient IDs inconsistently, which downstream step is most directly weakened first?**\r\n\r\nA. Interpretation, because dashboards will look odd\r\n\r\nB. Structure and retrieval, because the same patient cannot be reliably linked across tables\r\n\r\nC. Capture, because the form will reject entries\r\n\r\nD. Decisions, because managers will refuse to act\r\n\r\n**27. Which statement best describes the relationship among Core Concepts, Let's Build, Terms Treasury, Review and Reflection, RAT, and Lab?**\r\n\r\nA. They are independent, and students may safely skip any of them\r\n\r\nB. They build on each other, moving from concepts and vocabulary toward readiness checks and applied transfer\r\n\r\nC. They are alternative formats covering exactly the same content\r\n\r\nD. They are graded sections, so reading the main chapter is optional\r\n\r\n**28. According to the Chapter 1 table about where each project reappears, which chapter range pairs advanced SQL for grade analytics in Let's Build with advanced SQL for appointment and revenue analytics in the PetVax lab?**\r\n\r\nA. Chapters 4-5\r\n\r\nB. Chapters 6-7\r\n\r\nC. Chapter 9\r\n\r\nD. Chapter 14\r\n\r\n**29. A reader argues, \"We could skip normalization and go straight to dashboards.\" Which Chapter 1 idea most directly refutes this argument?**\r\n\r\nA. The book uses Bloom's Taxonomy\r\n\r\nB. The sequence is cumulative; trustworthy analytics cannot be built from messy data definitions\r\n\r\nC. The book includes a digital companion repository\r\n\r\nD. Power BI requires a license\r\n\r\n**30. Select ALL that apply: Which consequences of a poorly designed database are described in Chapter 1?**\r\n\r\nA. Duplicate records\r\n\r\nB. Inconsistent reports\r\n\r\nC. Faster query performance\r\n\r\nD. Missing information\r\n\r\nE. Confusing dashboards\r\n\r\n**31. Select ALL that apply: Which statements accurately describe how Chapter 1 positions tools versus workflow?**\r\n\r\nA. The tools differ, but the workflow is connected\r\n\r\nB. The book's goal is to memorize every button in every platform\r\n\r\nC. Each tool fits into a larger workflow from collection to communication\r\n\r\nD. Choosing the most modern tool is the most important decision\r\n\r\nE. Understanding what each tool is good for matters more than mastering every feature\r\n\r\n**32. A student says, \"I learned SQL in another class, but I do not really know why it matters.\" Which Chapter 1 design choice is most directly aimed at this gap?**\r\n\r\nA. The use of GitHub for companion materials\r\n\r\nB. Business meaning first: technical work appears in context, not in isolation\r\n\r\nC. The inclusion of AI-supported workflows\r\n\r\nD. The use of diagramming tools",
