            "id": "ch02-rat-page-3",
            "slug": "rat-page-3",
            "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 3",
            "content": "## Understand Questions\r\n\r\n**9. A supermarket manager sees a report showing dairy products sell faster on weekends. What DIKW level does this report represent?**\r\n\r\nA. Data\r\n\r\nB. Information\r\n\r\nC. Knowledge\r\n\r\nD. Wisdom\r\n\r\n**10. Select ALL that apply: Why does the chapter argue that data quality is a management issue rather than only a technical one?**\r\n\r\nA. Poor data quality distorts KPIs\r\n\r\nB. Inaccurate data can mislead managers\r\n\r\nC. Data quality problems reduce trust in systems\r\n\r\nD. Only IT staff can fix data quality problems\r\n\r\nE. Poor data quality confuses customers\r\n\r\n**11. In the chapter's online retailer example, why would tracking on-time delivery percentage be considered a KPI?**\r\n\r\nA. Because it is a number displayed on a dashboard\r\n\r\nB. Because it signals progress toward the important goal of delivery reliability\r\n\r\nC. Because it is calculated by the IT department\r\n\r\nD. Because it measures how fast the website loads\r\n\r\n**12. How does the chapter describe the relationship between efficiency and effectiveness?**\r\n\r\nA. They mean the same thing\r\n\r\nB. Efficiency is about doing things right; effectiveness is about doing the right things\r\n\r\nC. Effectiveness is always more important than efficiency\r\n\r\nD. Efficiency guarantees effectiveness\r\n\r\n**13. Select ALL that apply: According to the chapter, what problems make formal information systems necessary as organizations grow?**\r\n\r\nA. Scale — people cannot manually coordinate large volumes of activity\r\n\r\nB. Memory — organizations need records that outlast individual employees\r\n\r\nC. Visibility — managers need reliable operational truth\r\n\r\nD. Marketing — larger organizations need stronger brands\r\n\r\nE. Control — standardized processes make auditing and comparison possible\r\n\r\n**14. In the chapter's five-part information system operating loop, what role does feedback play?**\r\n\r\nA. It captures raw data from business activity\r\n\r\nB. It stores data for later retrieval\r\n\r\nC. It uses output to adjust inputs, processes, or decisions, closing the learning cycle\r\n\r\nD. It delivers information through reports and dashboards\r\n\r\n**15. According to Wilson's information behavior model discussed in the chapter, what is an \"information need\"?**\r\n\r\nA. The amount of data stored in a database\r\n\r\nB. The gap between what a person knows and what they need to know to solve a problem\r\n\r\nC. The speed at which a dashboard refreshes\r\n\r\nD. The number of reports an organization produces each week\r\n\r\n**16. What does the chapter identify as the key difference between Information Technology (IT) and an Information System (IS)?**\r\n\r\nA. IT is hardware; IS is software\r\n\r\nB. IT is the tools; IS is the coordinated arrangement of people, processes, data, and technology\r\n\r\nC. IT is for large companies; IS is for small businesses\r\n\r\nD. There is no meaningful difference",
