            "id": "ch02-rat-page-5",
            "slug": "rat-page-5",
            "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 5",
            "content": "## Analyze Questions\r\n\r\n**25. Select ALL that apply: In the chapter's IT/IS/MIS/BITM comparison, which statements are correct?**\r\n\r\nA. IT is the toolbox; IS is the workshop\r\n\r\nB. MIS focuses on the managerial use of information\r\n\r\nC. BITM focuses on managing technology as a strategic business resource\r\n\r\nD. IS and IT mean the same thing\r\n\r\nE. BITM asks which technologies the organization should invest in and how to govern them\r\n\r\n**26. A company installs an expensive analytics platform that generates impressive-looking dashboards. However, the underlying data comes from spreadsheets with inconsistent naming and duplicate entries. Using the chapter's concepts, what is the most fundamental problem?**\r\n\r\nA. The dashboards are poorly designed\r\n\r\nB. The company chose the wrong analytics platform\r\n\r\nC. The data-to-performance chain is broken at the foundation — poor data quality undermines everything built on it\r\n\r\nD. The company does not have enough KPIs\r\n\r\n**27. A manager receives a weekly report showing that Product A sales dropped 15 percent. The report does not include comparison data from prior periods, inventory levels, or promotion history. Applying the chapter's definition of information versus data, what is the problem?**\r\n\r\nA. The report contains too much data\r\n\r\nB. The 15 percent figure is data, not information — it lacks the context needed for interpretation\r\n\r\nC. Sales reports should never include percentages\r\n\r\nD. The manager should ask for a daily report instead\r\n\r\n**28. Select ALL that apply: According to the chapter, what distinguishes an operational decision from a strategic decision?**\r\n\r\nA. Operational decisions have a shorter time horizon\r\n\r\nB. Strategic decisions use less data\r\n\r\nC. Operational decisions often use current status data and task queues\r\n\r\nD. Strategic decisions involve forecasts, scenarios, and investment analysis\r\n\r\nE. Operational decisions are made only by senior executives\r\n\r\n**29. A hospital implements a new patient-records system. The hardware is reliable and the software functions correctly, but doctors resist using it because it adds 12 minutes of data entry per patient visit with no perceived benefit to care quality. Which component(s) of the five-component framework explain the failure?**\r\n\r\nA. Hardware only\r\n\r\nB. Software only\r\n\r\nC. Processes and people\r\n\r\nD. Data only\r\n\r\n**30. In the chapter, strategic alignment is defined as the principle that systems should support organizational goals. Which scenario best illustrates a misalignment?**\r\n\r\nA. A cost-focused retailer investing heavily in personalization features that customers never use\r\n\r\nB. A university installing a student information system\r\n\r\nC. A hospital implementing a patient safety tracking system\r\n\r\nD. A delivery company building a route optimization tool\r\n\r\n**31. Select ALL that apply: According to the chapter's discussion of IT governance, which questions fall under governance rather than day-to-day system administration?**\r\n\r\nA. Who decides which systems are built or purchased?\r\n\r\nB. Who owns the data?\r\n\r\nC. What server should host the database?\r\n\r\nD. How does the organization know whether a system creates value?\r\n\r\nE. Who can change records, reports, or system settings?\r\n\r\n**32. The chapter describes Brynjolfsson's productivity paradox. What does this paradox suggest about measuring technology value?**\r\n\r\nA. Technology investment always produces immediate, measurable returns\r\n\r\nB. The benefits of IT may be delayed, distributed, or difficult to isolate\r\n\r\nC. Technology never improves productivity\r\n\r\nD. Only manufacturing companies benefit from IT",
