            "id": "ch04-rat-page-4",
            "slug": "rat-page-4",
            "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 4",
            "content": "## Apply Questions\r\n\r\n**17. In the PetVax Lab 03 scenario, Sarah Perry's email was updated in one appointment row but not in others. Which anomaly does this illustrate?**\r\n\r\nA. Insertion anomaly\r\nB. Update anomaly\r\nC. Deletion anomaly\r\nD. Compression anomaly\r\n\r\n**18. In the PetVax scenario, Rex could not be recorded in the system until he had an appointment. Which Chapter 4 concept explains why this is a problem?**\r\n\r\nA. Data independence\r\nB. Insertion anomaly — one fact (pet exists) cannot be added without another fact (appointment)\r\nC. Program-data dependence\r\nD. Physical view separation\r\n\r\n**19. A table named `STUDENT_GRADE` has a column `StudentID` defined as `INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES STUDENT(StudentID)`. What does the `REFERENCES` clause enforce?**\r\n\r\nA. That `StudentID` in `STUDENT_GRADE` must match an existing `StudentID` in the `STUDENT` table\r\nB. That `STUDENT_GRADE` is a copy of the `STUDENT` table\r\nC. That students are automatically sorted by ID\r\nD. That `StudentID` is the only column in the table\r\n\r\n**20. In the chapter's Grading Database, which field would be the best choice for a primary key in the `STUDENT` table?**\r\n\r\nA. FirstName\r\nB. Email\r\nC. StudentID\r\nD. Birthday\r\n\r\n**21. Select ALL that apply: In the chapter's Let's Build Access activity, the `GRADEBOOK` table includes student attributes (FirstName, LastName, Email) alongside grade data. What problems would this structure create as the database grows?**\r\n\r\nA. Updating a student's email requires editing every grade row for that student\r\nB. A student's name and email are repeated in every row where they appear\r\nC. The table mixes two subjects — students and grades — that should be separated\r\nD. The table cannot store more than 255 characters per row\r\nE. Deleting the only grade for a student removes the only record that the student exists\r\n\r\n**22. The SQL statement `CREATE TABLE STUDENT (StudentID INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, Email TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE)` uses three constraints. Which of the following correctly identifies what `PRIMARY KEY` alone enforces?**\r\n\r\nA. That StudentID is auto-incremented by one for each new row\r\nB. That StudentID must be unique and cannot be NULL\r\nC. That StudentID can be used only once per database\r\nD. That StudentID must be a text value\r\n\r\n**23. A database has a `PET` table with `PetID` as primary key and an `APPOINTMENT` table with `PetID` referencing `PET(PetID)`. What happens if someone tries to insert an appointment with `PetID = 99` when no pet with `PetID = 99` exists in the `PET` table?**\r\n\r\nA. The appointment is created with a warning\r\nB. The DBMS rejects the insertion because the foreign key constraint is violated\r\nC. The DBMS automatically creates a new pet with PetID = 99\r\nD. The appointment is created and PetID is changed to match the nearest existing pet\r\n\r\n**24. Select ALL that apply: In Chapter 4's file environment comparison table, which traits belong to the database approach rather than the file environment?**\r\n\r\nA. Separate tables for different subjects\r\nB. Shared facts stored once and referenced by key\r\nC. Formulas that simulate connections between sheets\r\nD. Constraints that enforce rules automatically\r\nE. One shared source of truth instead of competing copies",
