            "id": "ch04-rat-page-6",
            "slug": "rat-page-6",
            "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 6",
            "content": "## Evaluate Questions\r\n\r\n**33. A small business stores customer data in a single spreadsheet with these columns: `CustomerID, Name, Email, OrderID, Product, Price, OrderDate`. As the business grows, which single change would most improve data reliability?**\r\n\r\nA. Add more color coding to distinguish different types of data\r\nB. Separate the data into related tables — CUSTOMER and ORDER — with a foreign key linking them\r\nC. Add more rows to the existing spreadsheet\r\nD. Convert the spreadsheet to a CSV file for faster loading\r\n\r\n**34. Select ALL that apply: A university department is choosing between keeping student records in shared spreadsheets and moving to a database. According to Chapter 4, which factors favor the database approach?**\r\n\r\nA. The data spans multiple related subjects (students, courses, grades, instructors) that must stay connected\r\nB. Multiple staff members need to update records concurrently\r\nC. The department wants to enforce rules such as \"scores must be between 0 and 100\"\r\nD. The department has fewer than 10 students total\r\nE. The department needs to ensure that deleting a course does not accidentally delete student records\r\n\r\n**35. Two database designs are proposed for a veterinary clinic. Design A uses one flat table: `VISIT(PetName, OwnerName, OwnerPhone, VisitDate, Service, Fee)`. Design B uses related tables: `PET(PetID, PetName, OwnerID)`, `OWNER(OwnerID, OwnerName, OwnerPhone)`, `VISIT(VisitID, PetID, VisitDate, Service, Fee)`. Which design does Chapter 4's reasoning support, and why?**\r\n\r\nA. Design A, because fewer tables are always easier to manage\r\nB. Design B, because separating subjects into related tables prevents redundancy, update anomalies, and the structural fragility that flat tables exhibit\r\nC. Design A, because all the data fits on one screen\r\nD. Design B, because databases require at least three tables by rule\r\n\r\n**36. Select ALL that apply: Chapter 4 describes constraints as rules that the DBMS enforces automatically. Which of the following protections do constraints provide?**\r\n\r\nA. NOT NULL ensures a value must be present — preventing missing data\r\nB. UNIQUE prevents duplicate values — ensuring each email or ID appears only once\r\nC. PRIMARY KEY combines NOT NULL and UNIQUE — guaranteeing each row has a reliable identity\r\nD. FOREIGN KEY prevents orphaned records — ensuring every reference points to something real\r\nE. CHECK automatically corrects invalid data to a valid value\r\n\r\n**37. The chapter's Let's Build uses Microsoft Access, but the chapter also discusses SQLite and PostgreSQL. When would an organization choose a server-based platform like PostgreSQL over a file-based platform like Access or SQLite?**\r\n\r\nA. When only one person ever needs to access the data\r\nB. When the organization needs multi-user concurrent access, strong typing, and production-style workflows\r\nC. When the database will contain fewer than 100 records\r\nD. When the database does not need to enforce any rules or constraints\r\n\r\n**38. Select ALL that apply: A database administrator is diagnosing why a report shows incorrect totals. Using Chapter 4's \"diagnose by layer\" approach, which layers should be investigated?**\r\n\r\nA. The stored structure — are the tables and relationships designed correctly?\r\nB. The DBMS settings — are constraints and rules enforced as expected?\r\nC. The application interface — does the form or report query the right fields?\r\nD. The human process — are people entering data consistently and correctly?\r\nE. The monitor cable — is the display connected properly?\r\n\r\n**39. An organization currently uses a single flat CSV file for all customer, order, and product data. A consultant recommends moving to a database. Based on Chapter 4, what is the strongest argument for following this recommendation?**\r\n\r\nA. CSV files are an outdated format that will stop working soon\r\nB. A database with related tables, primary keys, foreign keys, and constraints would prevent the redundancy, anomalies, and governance conflicts that are inevitable in a single flat file as data grows\r\nC. Databases are required by law for any business with customers\r\nD. CSV files cannot be opened on modern computers\r\n\r\n**40. Select ALL that apply: Chapter 4 states that \"valid SQL can still produce weak insight.\" Which scenarios illustrate this warning?**\r\n\r\nA. A query correctly averages a StudentID column — the SQL is valid, but the result has no business meaning\r\nB. A SELECT statement returns data from the wrong table because the analyst misunderstood the schema\r\nC. A query runs successfully but the underlying data has inconsistent definitions of \"customer\" across source systems\r\nD. SQL syntax errors prevent a query from executing\r\nE. A correctly written JOIN produces results, but the analyst interprets them as actual matches when they should have used a different join type",
