    "id": "ch01-rat-page-3",
    "slug": "rat-page-3",
    "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 3",
    "content": "## Understand Questions\r\n\r\n**9. Why does Chapter 1 argue that database design has business consequences?**\r\n\r\nA. Because databases are expensive to license\r\n\r\nB. Because structure shapes what an organization can see, measure, report, and improve\r\n\r\nC. Because most managers prefer relational databases over spreadsheets\r\n\r\nD. Because cloud databases scale better than on-premises systems\r\n\r\n**10. In the chapter's explanation, what is the main difference between guided practice with the Grading Database and transfer practice with PetVax?**\r\n\r\nA. Guided practice uses SQL while transfer practice avoids SQL\r\n\r\nB. Guided practice is graded while transfer practice is optional\r\n\r\nC. Guided practice teaches structure in a familiar setting; transfer practice asks students to apply the same logic in a new business context\r\n\r\nD. Guided practice uses Access while transfer practice uses Power BI\r\n\r\n**11. Why does Chapter 1 say students should start with the business question before writing a query?**\r\n\r\nA. Because SQL only runs after the question is documented\r\n\r\nB. Because writing the question clarifies what the query should measure and why it matters\r\n\r\nC. Because the question is required by most database management systems\r\n\r\nD. Because Power BI cannot read queries without a question header\r\n\r\n**12. Which statement best describes systems thinking as Chapter 1 defines it?**\r\n\r\nA. Memorizing database terminology\r\n\r\nB. Choosing the most modern database software\r\n\r\nC. Seeing how data, structure, analysis, and decisions work together\r\n\r\nD. Building one large spreadsheet that holds all company data\r\n\r\n**13. In the coffee shop example, why does the owner struggle with questions such as which ingredients are wasted most often?**\r\n\r\nA. Because spreadsheets cannot store text data\r\n\r\nB. Because sales, inventory, suppliers, and menu items are tracked separately with inconsistent names\r\n\r\nC. Because Power BI is not installed on the shop's computer\r\n\r\nD. Because the SQL standard does not allow waste calculations\r\n\r\n**14. Select ALL that apply: According to Chapter 1, which statements describe what makes this book different from typical MIS or database texts?**\r\n\r\nA. It puts business meaning before technical work\r\n\r\nB. It treats SQL syntax as the primary learning goal\r\n\r\nC. It teaches one continuous system narrative across chapters\r\n\r\nD. It uses guided practice followed by transfer practice\r\n\r\nE. It avoids treating any one tool as the whole workflow\r\n\r\n**15. Select ALL that apply: Which statements correctly describe the role of the Grading Database in Chapter 1?**\r\n\r\nA. It is the applied lab case that students complete independently\r\n\r\nB. It is the guided instructional case for Let's Build sections\r\n\r\nC. Its familiar academic domain helps students focus on database logic\r\n\r\nD. It is previewed as a project that can eventually support grade retrieval, attendance percentages, and reports\r\n\r\nE. It is the case used to teach PetVax clinical operations directly\r\n\r\n**16. According to Chapter 1, what is the main purpose of including Bloom's Taxonomy in the book's design?**\r\n\r\nA. To match reading quizzes to lab assignments\r\n\r\nB. To rank students by ability\r\n\r\nC. To move students from recognizing terms to building things with them\r\n\r\nD. To replace traditional letter grades",
