    "id": "ch01-rat-page-6",
    "slug": "rat-page-6",
    "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 6",
    "content": "## Evaluate Questions\r\n\r\n**33. Two student teams propose study plans. Team A reads each main chapter only. Team B reads the main chapter, then uses Let's Build, Terms, Review and Reflection, RAT, and Lab. Based on Chapter 1, which plan is stronger and why?**\r\n\r\nA. Team A, because main chapters cover all material\r\n\r\nB. Team B, because the companion sections move students from recognition to application and transfer\r\n\r\nC. Team A, because reading is the only assessed activity\r\n\r\nD. Team B, but only for students aiming for an A grade\r\n\r\n**34. A manager must choose where to invest first: a new dashboarding tool or a redesign of inconsistent source tables. Using Chapter 1's logic, which choice is better justified?**\r\n\r\nA. The dashboarding tool, because managers want visuals\r\n\r\nB. The dashboarding tool, because BigQuery is mentioned in the chapter\r\n\r\nC. The source-table redesign, because trustworthy analytics depend on structured, reliable data\r\n\r\nD. Either choice is equally valid\r\n\r\n**35. Which critique is strongest for an analytics report whose underlying database has duplicate customer records?**\r\n\r\nA. The report uses the wrong color palette\r\n\r\nB. The report's metrics may be inflated or fragmented because the database cannot reliably link records to a single customer\r\n\r\nC. The report should be built in Access instead of Power BI\r\n\r\nD. The report violates the chapter's SQL Pattern callout\r\n\r\n**36. Among the five core competencies, which one does Chapter 1 position as the most integrative because it combines technical reasoning with business context to recommend decisions?**\r\n\r\nA. Foundational information literacy\r\n\r\nB. Applied database management\r\n\r\nC. Data integrity and system quality\r\n\r\nD. Strategic problem solving\r\n\r\n**37. A student claims, \"Errors and failed queries mean I am not cut out for this course.\" Based on Chapter 1, which response is best justified?**\r\n\r\nA. Agree; database work requires natural talent\r\n\r\nB. Disagree; the chapter frames errors as clues and resilient problem solving as a success habit\r\n\r\nC. Agree; the chapter says students should avoid mistakes\r\n\r\nD. Disagree; the chapter says errors do not occur in well-designed databases\r\n\r\n**38. Select ALL that apply: Which study habits are most defensible for a student starting this course, based directly on Chapter 1?**\r\n\r\nA. Start with the business question before writing a query\r\n\r\nB. Skip companion materials to save time\r\n\r\nC. Treat small design choices as having large downstream consequences\r\n\r\nD. Use errors as clues rather than signs of failure\r\n\r\nE. Wait until the final week to inspect the digital companion files\r\n\r\n**39. Select ALL that apply: An employer asks an entry-level analyst to question a number in a weekly report. Which Chapter 1 competencies most directly support doing this well?**\r\n\r\nA. Performance-oriented analysis\r\n\r\nB. Data integrity and system quality\r\n\r\nC. Foundational information literacy\r\n\r\nD. Cloud network engineering\r\n\r\nE. Strategic problem solving\r\n\r\n**40. Two analysts must explain a misleading metric to leadership. Analyst A blames the dashboarding tool. Analyst B traces the issue back through queries, tables, relationships, and capture. Which response better reflects Chapter 1's framing of systems thinking?**\r\n\r\nA. Analyst A, because the dashboard is what leadership sees\r\n\r\nB. Analyst B, because systems thinking traces problems through the data-to-decisions arc\r\n\r\nC. Analyst A, because tools drive performance\r\n\r\nD. Both are equally defensible",
