    "id": "ch04-rat-page-1",
    "slug": "rat-page-1",
    "title": "Readiness Assessment Test (RAT): Chapter 4 — Introduction to Databases",
    "content": "# Readiness Assessment Test (RAT): Chapter 4 — Introduction to Databases\r\n\r\n<p align=\"center\">\r\n  <img src=\"https://res.cloudinary.com/dkndq6lyz/image/upload/f_auto/q_auto/RAT_nqr5a3?_a=BAMAAAX00\" alt=\"RAT or Quiz section icon\" width=\"220\">\r\n</p>\r\n<p align=\"center\">\r\n\r\n## Assessment Design Notes\r\n\r\nThis RAT checks whether students completed the Chapter 4 reading and can reason with database fundamentals — the DBMS/application/database architecture, flat-file anomalies, relational table rules, primary and foreign keys, constraints, and the bridge from spreadsheets to structured database systems. Questions are grounded in the Grading Database examples, the PetVax Lab 03 connections, the Let's Build Access activities, and chapter-specific SQL and table structures.\r\n\r\n### Bloom Distribution\r\n\r\n| Bloom Level | Questions | Count |\r\n|---|---|---|\r\n| Remember | 1–8 | 8 |\r\n| Understand | 9–16 | 8 |\r\n| Apply | 17–24 | 8 |\r\n| Analyze | 25–32 | 8 |\r\n| Evaluate | 33–40 | 8 |\r\n\r\n### Design Criterion Coverage\r\n\r\n| Design Criterion | Bloom Sections Used | Questions | Count |\r\n|---|---|---|---|\r\n| Application-based | Apply, Analyze, Evaluate | 17–24, 26, 28, 30, 32, 34–36, 38, 40 | 14 |\r\n| Scenario-based | Understand, Apply, Analyze, Evaluate | 10, 12–14, 18, 21, 27, 29, 31, 35, 37 | 12 |\r\n| Definition-only | Remember, Understand | 1–9, 11, 15, 16, 25 | 14 |\r\n\r\n### AI-Resistance Strategies Used\r\n\r\n1. **Chapter-specific reasoning** — questions reference the Grading Database tables (`STUDENT`, `STUDENT_GRADE`), PetVax Lab 03 scenarios (Coco, Angel, Rex, Sarah Perry), and the Let's Build Access `GRADEBOOK` table structure.\r\n2. **Schema-specific context** — questions use exact column names, constraint types, and key definitions from the chapter's SQL and data dictionary examples.\r\n3. **Scenario stems with embedded traps** — distractors drawn from adjacent concepts (surrogate vs. natural key, foreign key vs. primary key, logical vs. physical view, file environment vs. database approach).\r\n4. **Multi-answer discrimination** — Select ALL questions require distinguishing database capabilities from spreadsheet features, or identifying all constraint types from a mix of real and invented ones.\r\n5. **Non-obvious correct answers** — paraphrased chapter language rather than keyword-matched definitions (e.g., \"query fragility\" rephrased as \"formulas that break when rows are added\").\r\n6. **Output prediction** — questions ask what would happen if a constraint were missing, a key were changed, or a flat file were updated incorrectly.\r\n7. **Platform-specific details** — questions reference Access AutoNumber, SQLite INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, and the chapter's CREATE TABLE constraint syntax.",
