    "id": "ch04-rat-page-3",
    "slug": "rat-page-3",
    "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 3",
    "content": "## Understand Questions\r\n\r\n**9. Why does Chapter 4 describe a database as \"not just a better spreadsheet\"?**\r\n\r\nA. Databases are cheaper than spreadsheet software\r\nB. A database is a structured system that stores related data, protects it with rules, and makes it reusable — beyond what spreadsheets can enforce\r\nC. Databases can display more colors than spreadsheets\r\nD. Spreadsheets cannot store text values\r\n\r\n**10. In the file environment, why does program-data dependence cause problems?**\r\n\r\nA. Programs run too slowly when connected to files\r\nB. Small changes to a file structure can break every program and report that depends on it\r\nC. Programs require internet access to read files\r\nD. Files automatically delete themselves after a set time period\r\n\r\n**11. Select ALL that apply: How does Chapter 4 distinguish a surrogate key from a natural key?**\r\n\r\nA. A surrogate key is auto-numbered by the system and has no business meaning\r\nB. A natural key uses a real-world attribute such as email or SSN\r\nC. A surrogate key can never be used as a primary key\r\nD. Natural keys never change, making them ideal for all situations\r\nE. Surrogate keys are stable and independent of real-world attributes that may change\r\n\r\n**12. Why does Chapter 4 say that a spreadsheet may look neat but still be unreliable?**\r\n\r\nA. Spreadsheets use too many colors and formatting options\r\nB. A spreadsheet can quietly allow inconsistent dates, duplicate records, missing values, and fragile relationships that are not obvious from its appearance\r\nC. Spreadsheets cannot store more than 100 rows\r\nD. Spreadsheets always crash when opened by multiple users\r\n\r\n**13. What is the purpose of a CHECK constraint?**\r\n\r\nA. To verify that the database server is running correctly\r\nB. To restrict a column's values to a defined range or rule, such as `Score BETWEEN 0 AND 100`\r\nC. To confirm that a backup was completed successfully\r\nD. To check whether a table has a primary key\r\n\r\n**14. Select ALL that apply: What does Chapter 4 identify as problems with the file environment approach?**\r\n\r\nA. Redundancy — the same fact is stored in many places\r\nB. Inconsistency — different copies stop matching each other\r\nC. Program-data dependence — programs are tied to specific file structures\r\nD. Files automatically optimize themselves for queries\r\nE. Competing copies create governance conflicts\r\n\r\n**15. How does data independence benefit an organization?**\r\n\r\nA. It allows the physical storage to be changed or optimized without breaking the applications and reports users rely on\r\nB. It guarantees that data will never be lost\r\nC. It eliminates the need for a database administrator\r\nD. It makes all queries run at the same speed regardless of complexity\r\n\r\n**16. In Chapter 4's layered architecture, what does the DBMS layer do that the database layer does not?**\r\n\r\nA. The DBMS stores the actual table data on disk\r\nB. The DBMS validates data, enforces rules and constraints, manages concurrent access, and optimizes queries — the database layer stores the structure\r\nC. The DBMS is the same thing as the database layer\r\nD. The DBMS provides the user interface for data entry",
