    "id": "ch04-rat-page-5",
    "slug": "rat-page-5",
    "title": "RAT: Reading Test — Page 5",
    "content": "## Analyze Questions\r\n\r\n**25. How does Chapter 4 distinguish the logical view of a database from the physical view?**\r\n\r\nA. The logical view shows table structures and relationships that users see; the physical view handles storage, indexing, and optimization that the DBMS manages behind the scenes\r\nB. The logical view is stored on disk; the physical view is stored in memory\r\nC. The logical view applies only to Access; the physical view applies only to PostgreSQL\r\nD. The logical view and physical view are the same thing viewed from different angles\r\n\r\n**26. Select ALL that apply: Chapter 4 describes eight rules of relational tables. Which of the following correctly state some of those rules?**\r\n\r\nA. Each table has a unique name\r\nB. Each cell holds one atomic value\r\nC. Rows can be duplicated to improve query performance\r\nD. Each row represents one instance of one entity\r\nE. Row and column order create meaning in the data\r\n\r\n**27. A company keeps customer data in departmental spreadsheets. Marketing has one version, Sales has another, and Customer Service has a third. According to Chapter 4, which specific database benefit would most directly address this problem?**\r\n\r\nA. Data independence — separating physical and logical views\r\nB. Centralized source of truth — everyone works from the same official data\r\nC. Concurrency control — managing simultaneous access\r\nD. Historical analysis — studying records over time\r\n\r\n**28. Select ALL that apply: Chapter 4 describes an architectural spectrum from local/file-based to server-based database platforms. What distinguishes the server-based end of this spectrum?**\r\n\r\nA. Multi-user concurrent access with conflict management\r\nB. Stronger typing and constraint enforcement\r\nC. No need for a DBMS — data is stored directly in files\r\nD. Production-style workflows suitable for organizational use\r\nE. Easier start-up with minimal setup required\r\n\r\n**29. In a flat grading file, deleting all quiz scores for a particular deliverable also removes any record that the deliverable type existed. Which anomaly is this, and what database feature prevents it?**\r\n\r\nA. Update anomaly, prevented by CHECK constraints\r\nB. Insertion anomaly, prevented by NOT NULL\r\nC. Deletion anomaly, prevented by separating deliverables and grades into related tables with foreign keys\r\nD. Compression anomaly, prevented by database indexing\r\n\r\n**30. The chapter states that Email could serve as a natural key but recommends a surrogate key like StudentID instead. Why?**\r\n\r\nA. Emails are too long to index efficiently\r\nB. Emails can change — a student may update their email, and changing a primary key is harder than changing an attribute\r\nC. Email addresses are not unique in practice\r\nD. Surrogate keys are required by SQL standards\r\n\r\n**31. Select ALL that apply: Chapter 4's PetVax connections show how Lab 03 problems map to database concepts. Which mappings are correct?**\r\n\r\nA. Sarah Perry's email changed in only one row → update anomaly → use separate tables with foreign keys\r\nB. Coco the pet had two owners → need for related tables → use a link table connecting pets to owners\r\nC. Fixed FILTER() range missed new rows → query fragility → use table/field names in SQL\r\nD. Angel's appointment deleted, erasing evidence Angel existed → deletion anomaly → store pet facts separately from appointments\r\nE. Two pets named Coco → need for better color coding in the spreadsheet\r\n\r\n**32. The chapter presents `CREATE TABLE STUDENT_GRADE (GradeID INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, StudentID INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES STUDENT(StudentID), Score NUMERIC CHECK (Score BETWEEN 0 AND 100))`. What would happen if the CHECK constraint were removed?**\r\n\r\nA. The table would no longer accept any rows\r\nB. Scores outside 0–100, such as 150 or -20, could be inserted without the DBMS rejecting them\r\nC. The foreign key constraint would also stop working\r\nD. The primary key would automatically become the CHECK column",
